{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-tsx","path":"/2019/03/28/blender-tutorial-14-armatures-character-rigging/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p><em>In this new post of the series Blender tutorial I will talk about armatures and character rigging.</em></p>\n<hr>\n<p>In the <a href=\"/2019/03/27/blender-tutorial-13-animation/\">previous post of the series \"Blender tutorial\"</a> we talked about\nanimation. In this post we will talk about armatures and character rigging.<br>\nLet's start from armatures. Armatures are composed of bones. We can create bones by selecting <em>Add -> Armature -> Single\nBone</em>. Every bone is compose of:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>a base</li>\n<li>a body</li>\n<li>a tip</li>\n</ul>\n<p>By selecting the body we can move the entire bone into a new position. By selecting the base or the tip we can move just\none of the end of the bone. When a bone is selected two new tab becomes available in the properties panel:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>the armature tab</li>\n<li>the bone tab</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Let's see the armature tab first. First we have a the display options, to manage how the bone is displayed. We can also\nshow the name, the color and more important we can activate the X-Ray mode that let us see the bone through the\ncharacter.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/7856e95d4a48e15232b99866ade8296b/c58a3/blender-bones.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 59.298245614035096%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Add bones\"\n        title=\"Add bones\"\n        src=\"/static/7856e95d4a48e15232b99866ade8296b/0470c/blender-bones.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/7856e95d4a48e15232b99866ade8296b/6c669/blender-bones.jpg 285w,\n/static/7856e95d4a48e15232b99866ade8296b/882a4/blender-bones.jpg 570w,\n/static/7856e95d4a48e15232b99866ade8296b/0470c/blender-bones.jpg 1140w,\n/static/7856e95d4a48e15232b99866ade8296b/c58a3/blender-bones.jpg 1500w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Add bones</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>To create a complete armature we have some tools similar to the one we previously seen for modeling. After selecting\nedit mode, in the left panel of the 3D window we have the options extrude and subdivide that let us create a complete\nskeleton for a character. In the scene we will find our armature object with all the bones connected.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/ee0fcef1f7e85111c80aead62f25867d/c58a3/blender-armature.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 59.298245614035096%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Add armature\"\n        title=\"Add armature\"\n        src=\"/static/ee0fcef1f7e85111c80aead62f25867d/0470c/blender-armature.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/ee0fcef1f7e85111c80aead62f25867d/6c669/blender-armature.jpg 285w,\n/static/ee0fcef1f7e85111c80aead62f25867d/882a4/blender-armature.jpg 570w,\n/static/ee0fcef1f7e85111c80aead62f25867d/0470c/blender-armature.jpg 1140w,\n/static/ee0fcef1f7e85111c80aead62f25867d/c58a3/blender-armature.jpg 1500w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Add armature</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>We can now start to add the armature to an object. To do that we just have to place/create the bones inside our object.\nAfter that we select the object and the bones (in this specific order), and we choose from the menu at the bottom of the\n3D window the option Object -> Parent -> Armature Deform. After this operation, we can go into pose mode (by choosing it\nin the menu at the bottom of the 3D window). If we move one of our bones in this mode, the part of the object/mesh that\ncontains that bone will move accordingly.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/3151e5b33f0c24fde828afd2a6954ae9/c58a3/blender-set-armature.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 59.298245614035096%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Set armature\"\n        title=\"Set armature\"\n        src=\"/static/3151e5b33f0c24fde828afd2a6954ae9/0470c/blender-set-armature.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/3151e5b33f0c24fde828afd2a6954ae9/6c669/blender-set-armature.jpg 285w,\n/static/3151e5b33f0c24fde828afd2a6954ae9/882a4/blender-set-armature.jpg 570w,\n/static/3151e5b33f0c24fde828afd2a6954ae9/0470c/blender-set-armature.jpg 1140w,\n/static/3151e5b33f0c24fde828afd2a6954ae9/c58a3/blender-set-armature.jpg 1500w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Set armature</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>\n        <div class=\"embedVideo-container\">\n            <iframe\n              title=\"\"\n              width=\"100%\"\n              height=\"auto\"\n              src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/GpkMgUqWZJo?rel=0\"\n              class=\"embedVideo-iframe\"\n              style=\"border:0\"\n              \n              loading=\"lazy\"\n              allowfullscreen\n\t      sandbox=\"allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-popups\"\n            ></iframe>\n        </div></p>\n<p>Sometimes we will also need to constraint a bone to the move of other bones. Instead of doing it manually, we can use\nInverse kinematics. To be more clear this is an extract of the blender doc:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>IK simplifies the animation process, and makes it possible to make more advanced animations with lesser effort. IK allows you to position the last bone in a bone chain and the other bones are positioned automatically</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>We can add an inverse kinematic constraint on a bone by choosing it from the menu under the Bone constraint tab in the\nproperties panel. This tab will appear only when we are in pose mode.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/248cb27500276a762de3c3a13fbce93e/c58a3/blender-inverse-kinematics.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.15789473684211%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Inverse kinematics\"\n        title=\"Inverse kinematics\"\n        src=\"/static/248cb27500276a762de3c3a13fbce93e/0470c/blender-inverse-kinematics.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/248cb27500276a762de3c3a13fbce93e/6c669/blender-inverse-kinematics.jpg 285w,\n/static/248cb27500276a762de3c3a13fbce93e/882a4/blender-inverse-kinematics.jpg 570w,\n/static/248cb27500276a762de3c3a13fbce93e/0470c/blender-inverse-kinematics.jpg 1140w,\n/static/248cb27500276a762de3c3a13fbce93e/c58a3/blender-inverse-kinematics.jpg 1500w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Inverse kinematics</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>After setting bones, armature and inverse kinematics we are ready to animate our character. To do that, we just need to\nbe in Pose mode and set the keyframes as we did for standard animation.</p>\n<p>\n        <div class=\"embedVideo-container\">\n            <iframe\n              title=\"\"\n              width=\"100%\"\n              height=\"auto\"\n              src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/Q5m1rnjT6Rw?rel=0\"\n              class=\"embedVideo-iframe\"\n              style=\"border:0\"\n              \n              loading=\"lazy\"\n              allowfullscreen\n\t      sandbox=\"allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-popups\"\n            ></iframe>\n        </div></p>\n<p>That's all for character rigging. In the next post we will talk about the rendering engine Cycles.</p>","frontmatter":{"title":"Blender tutorial: armatures and character rigging","comments":true,"authors":["fabrizio_duroni"],"tags":["computer graphics","blender"],"date":"28 Mar 2019","description":"In this new post of the series Blender tutorial I will talk about character rigging.","math":false,"image":{"childImageSharp":{"gatsbyImageData":{"layout":"fullWidth","backgroundColor":"#f8f8f8","images":{"fallback":{"src":"/static/7856e95d4a48e15232b99866ade8296b/6e588/blender-bones.jpg","srcSet":"/static/7856e95d4a48e15232b99866ade8296b/86f08/blender-bones.jpg 750w,\n/static/7856e95d4a48e15232b99866ade8296b/f8f47/blender-bones.jpg 1080w,\n/static/7856e95d4a48e15232b99866ade8296b/e1813/blender-bones.jpg 1366w,\n/static/7856e95d4a48e15232b99866ade8296b/6e588/blender-bones.jpg 1500w","sizes":"100vw"},"sources":[{"srcSet":"/static/7856e95d4a48e15232b99866ade8296b/a83d3/blender-bones.webp 750w,\n/static/7856e95d4a48e15232b99866ade8296b/d3691/blender-bones.webp 1080w,\n/static/7856e95d4a48e15232b99866ade8296b/2af58/blender-bones.webp 1366w,\n/static/7856e95d4a48e15232b99866ade8296b/3550c/blender-bones.webp 1500w","type":"image/webp","sizes":"100vw"}]},"width":1,"height":0.594}}}},"fields":{"slug":"/2019/03/28/blender-tutorial-14-armatures-character-rigging/","readingTime":{"text":"3 min read"}}},"site":{"siteMetadata":{"author":"Fabrizio Duroni"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/2019/03/28/blender-tutorial-14-armatures-character-rigging/"}},"staticQueryHashes":["3076394108","3736063423","4028829600","4159577854"]}